{"key":"post-8612710","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>8612710</id>\n<content>I've filled in the gaps and left them open.&amp;nbsp; It really doesn't make much difference if you don't mind side pins, which usually end up healthier anyway.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;The reason a colonized substrate shrinks from flush to flush regardless of dunking/soaking is that the mycelium is actually &lt;i&gt;eating&lt;/i&gt; the substrate for food.&amp;nbsp; That's a major difference between mushrooms and plants.&amp;nbsp; You can grow a plant in the same pot of soil for years by adding nutrients.&amp;nbsp; Not so with fungi.&amp;nbsp; They continue to 'eat' their substrate until nothing is left.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>8612739</next>\n<prev>8612521</prev>\n<first>8612344</first>\n<last>8612739</last>\n<when>1215624975</when>\n<utime>07/09/08 08:36 PM</utime>\n</post>"}